LEAF PAINTING 🍁🍂🍃🌿- I’m reposting this fun LIVE I did with @mastermindtoys on Friday because there are so many fun leaf painting techniques! And I love that you can use so many different kinds of paint and supplies to make beautiful art 🤩 Sorry the sound is a little off 🙈 the Lives can do that. Let me know in the comments below if you guys would like to see more craft and art tutorial lives! ❤️
.
.
Here’s what you need:
-Leaves 🍂🍁🌿
-Paint - we used watercolors, acrylic and puffy paint (special thanks to @colormadehappy for the puffy paint idea)
-White cardstock 
.
.
For the full post head to thebestideasforkids.com and search “Leaf Painting” or head to: https://www.thebestideasforkids.com/leaf-painting/
.
.
Follow us at @bestideasforkids for more fun kids crafts and activities 🌈 🎨 
.
.
For the giveaway by @mastermindtoys this is open to Canadian residents 18+. This giveaway is not affiliated or endorsed by Instagram. 
.
.
.
.
.
.

APPLE HANDPRINT CARDS 🤚 🍎 🍏 

Here’s a cute card to make for back to school! 🏫 

We used @artezaofficial tempera kids washable paint to make this cards. The coverage on this paint is the BEST I have ever seen for washable paint. So so impressed! 
@artezaofficial is having a back to school promotion and I’ll share the details in my stories soon! They have everything you need to get ready for back to school with kids!

Here’s how to make the cards:

1. Fold over a piece of white cardstock
2. Paint the hand with Arteza washable tempera paint. We used neon green, fire truck red and banana yellow. 
3. Print the handprint so that the thumb is along the folded part. You want the handprint upside down to make the apple.
4. Let the paint dry and cut out the handprint card.
5. Paint a stem and leaf. Then outline them with an Arteza black acrylic marker.
6. Add eyes, cheeks and a smile with the Arteza acrylic markers.

Make these for back to school or as a new teacher gift! 😍🍎🍏 (sponsored) 
#arteza #B2Switharteza

WALKING WATER 💧 RAINBOW 🌈
Here’s another easy science 🧪 experiment with just water, food coloring and paper towel 🤩 We loved learning about color mixing to build this walking rainbow 🌈 .

Here’s how to do it: 
1. Add red food coloring to 2 cups
2. Blue food coloring to 1 cup 
3. Yellow food coloring to 1 cup
4. Line up the cups as shown with blank cups in between
5. Fold over a half sheet of paper towel and place into each cup, connecting with the empty cups (this is where the color will travel to) 
6. Wait 3 hours and the color will travel from the paper towel and mix with the color on the other side to make orange, green and purple 😍
.
Follow me at @bestideasforkids for more fun kid craft ideas. 🖍✂️
.
.
To get the full details on this experiment, Search “Walking Water” on thebestideasforkids.com. .

FROZEN DINOSAUR EGGS 🥚 🦕 🦖 
When you’re in a pinch and need something that will keep the kids busy, just freeze stuff 😆 My kids always love this activity. 

Swipe 👉 to see a version with dinosaur fossil toys you can make to do a pretend dinosaur excavation too! 🔍 🦴 

How to make the frozen dinosaur eggs: 
- Save your used balloons! 🎈 (Must be 12 inch size or larger)
-Cut off the tied part as close as possible.
-Open the balloon and place a mini dinosaur inside. You may need a helping hand to do this!
-Fill the balloon with water 💦 Because the tip is cut off, hold the end to the faucet when filling it up so that the water doesn’t overflow out of the balloon
-Now the tricky part- stretch as far as possible to retie. This is tricker because the balloon is smaller but it is possible! 
-Freeze until frozen 🥶 
-Now kids can use warm water and droppers to “hatch” the eggs 🥚

🧂 SALT PAINTING 🧂 🎨
We love salt painting. It’s one of my favorite art activities. 🤩
The first one we did were some snowflakes ❄️ a few years back and the possibilities are endless 🙌

Here’s how to do it:
-Trace or draw a picture with glue on white cardstock 
-Add salt on top. Shake off any excess.
-Tap gently with some liquid watercolors (liquid gel food coloring would work too or regular watercolors just don’t add too much water to keep the colors vibrant)
Tip: it works best if you paint right away 🎨 
.
Follow me at @bestideasforkids for more fun kid craft ideas. 🖍✂️

You can get this template by searching “spring salt painting” on thebestideasforkids.com

SPONGE BALLS 🧽 💦💧
.
Save this for your next water 💦 fight 🤩 We love that these balls soak up so much water and are reusable. ♻️ 

To make them ✂️ you need 3 sponges per ball. 🧽 Cut each sponge into 3 strips. You need 9 strips per ball, then tie together with a string or elastic. Tie as tightly as you can do that the pieces flare out. You may need to double tie.

FIZZY RAINBOW 🌈  If you’re ever in a pinch to bust boredom, meet my favorite activity: baking soda and vinegar. This activity never gets old! I decided to make a whole baking soda rainbow 🌈 and the kids loved adding vinegar to it to see the bubbly reaction 🤩
.
How to make it 🙌
To make RED, ORANGE, and YELLOW: Mix 1 cup of baking soda with 3 tablespoons of water (mix 1 drop of liquid food coloring gel to the water first). For GREEN, BLUE, and PURPLE we halved the recipe since you don’t need as much to make the rainbow. Add to a tray and then use droppers to drop the vinegar on it. 💧
For a different twist you can add colored vinegar onto the white baking soda too!

PAPER ROLL FLOWER STAMPS 🌸🌼🌺🌻 -  such a fun way to recycle paper rolls into an art activity! 

How to make them:
1. Cut slits all around the paper roll.
2. Cut 5 petals out of the top of the paper roll.
3. Fold the paper roll in half and dip in paint to make 2 petals when you stamp. 

This is from our my recycled craft for kids book - Fun and Easy Crafting with Recycled Materials! 🎨 Info in my Page highlight ❤️

FROG FOLDING SURPRISE 🐸 
Looking for a simple activity that doesn’t require any prep?! 🙌

This surprise frog craft 🐸 is not only easy to make - but kids love to play with the opening and closing of the surprise! 

It’s easy to fold- just fold the paper down, then fold the top piece up. Now the mouth goes from closed to open! 

DM me if you want the free template - or head to thebestideasforkids.com and get it on the post.

ICE CHALK 🌈 - a fun summer activity perfect for all those bits and pieces of leftover chalk 👌 and if you’re asking.. why? 😱 This is a great sensory activity for kids. It’s something new to try outside and the kids can even help you make them. You can make larger batches by freezing in small lunch containers like salad dressing containers or using a bigger ice cube mold. 

Here’s how to make it ✨

Grate or use a rolling pin to smash up half of a piece of sidewalk chalk.

Add 2 tablespoons of cornstarch into the measuring cup.

Add 4 tablespoons of water. 

Mix with a whisk.
Pour the mixture into an ice cube tray or small plastic container.

Repeat for each color you'd like to make. Double or triple the recipe to make a larger batch. This recipe will fill 2-3 ice cubes.

Add mini popsicle sticks into the ice cube trays. You can lean them to one side to keep them standing up.

Freeze.
Once frozen, let the ice cube tray sit out for a few minutes so that you can easily pull the paintsicles out.

Have fun 🤩 🥳🌈

.

MOON SAND 🏖 (taste safe 👅)
We’ve seen moon sand made a few times and typically it calls for 8 cups of flour to 1 cup of oil. Since flour is raw before being cooked, it’s not taste safe for kids. So the first time we saw taste safe sand was by our friend @mothercould be sure to check it out as she has a different method 🤩
.
I wanted to see if I could make a taste safe sand with cornstarch 👌 and made this amazing sand that looks 👀 like sand and smells 👃 like the beach 🏖 🥥 My kids even said they prefer it to regular sand! 🙌 

Note- while taste safe, we don’t recommend you allow kids actually eat it so as always, supervise during play. 

Here’s what you need:
- 1 cup of cornstarch 
- 1 cup of light brown sugar
- 4 tablespoons of coconut oil 🥥 (melted before adding). 

Note: To make this taste safe, bake the cornstarch in advance in the oven. Place the cornstarch on a baking tray and spread it out. Bake at 300 degrees Fahrenheit for 10 minutes. Allow to cool before making the recipe.

Make sure to whisk and mix together until all of the clumps are gone.
